parameters.bodyContent:
=

Hi {{ $('Webhook').item.json.body.data.conversation_initiation_client_data.dynamic_variables.first_name }},

Here’s your matter summary based on our conversation:

{{ $json.matter.heading }}
D1 Name of client – this will be publishable. If you cannot reveal the client’s name, give a general description.
{{ $json.matter.D1.client_name }}
D2 Summary of matter and your department's role – Please say why this matter was important. Also, tell us exactly what role your department played.
{{ $json.matter.D2.formatted_output }}
D3 Matter value – include currency and amount in figures
{{ $json.matter.D3.formatted_output }}
D4 Is this a cross-border matter? If yes, please indicate the jurisdictions involved.
{{ $json.matter.D4.formatted_output }}
D5 Lead lawyer
{{ $json.matter.D5.formatted_output }}
D6 Other team members
{{ $json.matter.D6.formatted_output }}
D7 Other firms advising on the matter and their role(s)
{{ $json.matter.D7.formatted_output }}
D8 Date of completion or current status
{{ $json.matter.D8.formatted_output }}
D9 Other information about this matter – e.g. link to press coverage
{{ $json.matter.D9.formatted_output }}
{{ $json.data }}

That’s everything for now — hope it was helpful. If you’d like to log another matter straight away, you can do it here.

Cheers,

Leonard

AI Assistant
Legal Engine

E: leonard@legalengine.co.uk
W: www.legalengine.co.uk

assignments.value:
Firm-Specific Tone, Style and Formatting Guide (Chambers-Compatible)
Overall Tone

Professional, neutral and evidence-driven.

Clean, precise prose that supports Chambers’ preference for narrative clarity.

Plain English, minimal adjectives, no hype.

Every sentence must advance significance, complexity or impact.

No em dashes. Use a full stop to start a new sentence, or a comma to continue.

Foundational Style Rules

UK English throughout.

Always use third person.

Short sentences.

Avoid rhetorical devices or idioms.

Use consistent formatting across all submissions.

Referencing Conventions
Clients

Default to anonymisation unless public.

Use a descriptive identifier on first mention and a shorter form afterwards.

Example: “A high-net-worth individual with global business interests” → “the client”.

Dates

Use DD Month YYYY.

Ranges: January to March 2025, 14 September 2024 to 12 January 2025.

Matter Value

Always include currency and figures in a clear, Chambers-friendly format.

Examples from E3 (to be followed precisely):

£30 million – £40 million

If a narrower range exists: £7m – £9m

If a single amount: £15,000

Use decimals only where meaningful: £40.5m.

For multi-currency: £40m (approx USD 50m).

Cross-Border Jurisdictions

If the matter is cross-border, clearly list all relevant jurisdictions.

Follow the E4 example format:

Yes, Sweden, France and the UK. Historic property held in New York, USA. Business interests in multiple jurisdictions. Trusts held in BVI before being moved to Liechtenstein.

Rules for the AI agent:

List jurisdictions cleanly, separated by commas or full stops.

Include historic locations where relevant to complexity.

Avoid narrative commentary — only facts.

Lawyer Referencing (Internal Team)

Use this strict order for every person:

Full name

Title

Firm (if needed)

Lead Lawyer Format (E5 example):

Hetty Gleave (Partner)

Other Team Members Format (E6 example):

The AI must follow this pattern exactly:

Rebecca Christie (Senior Associate, Fladgate), Jonathan Riley (Partner, Fladgate), Elizabeth Clarke (‘Star individual’ junior counsel, QEB), Amy Kisser (Band 1 junior counsel, QEB), James Ewins KC (Band 1 silk, QEB), Alexander Thorpe KC, Jessica O’Driscoll Breen, Andrew Campbell (all barristers at QEB)

Formatting rules derived from this example:

Use commas to separate individuals.

Include titles and rankings where known.

If several barristers are at the same chambers, you may group them (“all barristers at QEB”).

KC/King’s Counsel is always appended to the name.

Rankings should appear in parentheses.

Other Firms and Counsel (E7 Example Standards)

Follow this precise structure for external advisers:

James Stewart (Partner) and Amy Fox (Partner), Penningtons Manches Cooper LLP (UHNW firm)
Deborah Bangay KC and Lily Mottahedan (Family: Matrimonial Finance), 1 Hare Court
Emma Hargreaves (Serle Court)

Formatting rules for the AI:

Start with full names.

Include titles where relevant.

End with the firm/chambers name.

If multiple advisers share the same set, place the set at the end.

No adjectives except Chambers/Legal 500 ranking terminology.

Matter Headline

Format:
Client name or identifier. Core issue
Examples:

“A high-net-worth client. Multi-jurisdictional divorce and trust restructuring”

“A global commodities group. High-value fraud and arbitration defence”

Matter Structure (Chambers-Compatible Narrative)

Every matter must follow this mini-case-study arc:

Client and Context

Concise description, anonymity where required.

Jurisdiction(s).

Nature of the matter.

Challenge and Complexity

Core legal, commercial or procedural issues.

Cross-border, regulatory, trust, or multi-party considerations.

Quantified value using the E3 format.

Strategy and Role

Team actions, critical decisions, innovative approaches.

Use active verbs.

Avoid promotional adjectives.

Outcome and Impact

Results achieved.

What was protected, won, avoided or unlocked.

Why it matters in the Chambers sense (precedent, strategic value).

Lawyers Involved

Follow E5 and E6 formats precisely.

Other Firms / Counsel Involved (if relevant)

Follow the E7 pattern.

Long Summary / Practice Overview

Firm preference: structured prose, short paragraphs, consistent with Chambers’ narrative expectations and Legal 500’s clarity principles.

Required order:

Overview of practice strengths.

Themes across the past year.

Integrated examples of high-impact matters.

Team depth, leadership and next-generation capability.

Market positioning and innovations.

What to avoid:

Bullet-point lists unless the directory template requires them.

Marketing superlatives not supported by evidence.

Long paragraphs without clear narrative direction.

Integration With Chambers Best Practice

This guide does not replace guidance in GUIDELINES 1–2.
It provides operational instructions so the AI agent outputs text that is:

stylistically consistent,

compliant with templates,

aligned with narrative storytelling requirements,

compatible with confidentiality and referee expectations,

formatted correctly (names, titles, values, jurisdictions),

suitable for immediate insertion into Chambers and Legal 500 forms.

Based in London for this matter, Andy Batty's work over the past 12 months involved active collaboration with iFood to integrate their technology platforms into a single corporate technology stack. This included extensive consultation on the legal implications of operating such a unified stack across South America and Europe, specifically addressing how European jurisdictions might perceive a "one-size-fits-all" technological approach. A particular focus was placed on the application of generative AI, noting its distinct connotations and legal considerations across different markets, a detail relevant to Andy Batty's involvement in his department's AI agent development. Earlier work facilitated the transition from Just Eat, understanding acquired assets, and planning future collaboration. The transaction required compliance with FCA rules, engagement with the European Commission, and involved banks such as Avian Amro, Royal Bank of Brazil, and Royal Bank of Ireland. Ultimately, Just Eat Takeaway sold its stake in iFood to Prosus due to activist stakeholder pressure. The diverse jurisdictions involved include the UK, Italy, Poland, Portugal, Germany, Austria, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Brazil, and the newly added Rwanda, with Greece no longer included. His supporting team for this matter consists of Lee Curtis (based in Dublin and handling HR matters, a different role and location from his Data Protection specialization for Brewdog), Charles Dickens (from the Netherlands, focusing on Data Protection), and Sam Stamp (from Hamburg, involved in HR). Okay, Andy. I'm looking at the "Brewdog HR/employment advice" matter.

This is an ongoing, publishable matter that began in January 2020. Its value recently increased from seven hundred thousand pounds to one million pounds Sterling. Over the past twelve months, the focus has been on protecting Brewdog's business, providing leadership support, conducting in-depth analysis for business optimization, and navigating the UK media landscape.

Does that sound correct?
Yeah.
Great. Is this matter confidential, or can it be published?
It can be published.
Understood. Can you confirm the client's name is Brewdog?
That's correct.
Thanks, Andy. Now, regarding the matter description, I have that it concerns HR and employment advice. Is there any...
transcript.original_message: Thanks, Andy. Now, regarding the matter description, I have that it concerns HR and employment advice. Is there any additional information or updates you'd like to add or clarify on this?

transcript.message: Yeah, so we need to also include the fact that we brought in our tax advisors to work on a private equity investment case. And so we had the tax expertise of Lucy Batty, who was based out of our Camberley office. And what we did over the last kind of 12 months was really to double down and focus in on the profitability of the business. So we decided we're going to close a proportion of our real estate locations and double down on the big iconic locations such as Waterloo.
That's a lot of important information, thank you. So, to clarify, the matter description should include the private equity investment case involving tax advisor Lucy Batty from...

So, to clarify, the matter description should include the private equity investment case involving tax advisor Lucy Batty from Camberley, and the strategic decision to close some real estate locations while focusing on key sites like Waterloo, all within the context of enhancing business profitability. Is that a correct summary?

transcript.message: Yeah.
And the focus over...
transcript.original_message: And the focus over the last twelve months has been on profitability, including closing some real estate locations and concentrating on key sites like Waterloo. Is that right?

transcript.message: Correct.

transcript.message: Yep. That's right.
And the focus over the last twelve months was on closing some real...
transcript.original_message: And the focus over the last twelve months was on closing some real estate locations and concentrating on profitability by doubling down on key sites like Waterloo. Is that a fair summary?

transcript.message: No, I've told you that

My apologies, Andy. I'll be more careful.

Now, regarding the department's role, what specific updates can you provide on the work your team completed in the past 12 months for this matter?
It's really what I've just told you so all about the tax efficiency and solving for profitability as part of a private equity deal
Thank you, Andy. And as this is an existing matter, why was it particularly important to your client, your firm, or the broader legal market? Was it precedent-setting?
Yeah it was just because it was very much in the public eye

Okay, thank you. Let me make sure I've captured this correctly.

The matter involved a private equity investment case where tax expertise was provided by Lucy Batty from the Camberley office. Over the past twelve months, the focus has been on improving the business's profitability by closing...

Okay, thank you. Let me make sure I've captured this correctly.

The matter involved a private equity investment case where tax expertise was provided by Lucy Batty from the Camberley office. Over the past twelve months, the focus has been on improving the business's profitability by closing some real estate locations and concentrating on key sites like Waterloo. This was particularly important as the matter was very much in the public eye.

Does that sound right?
